Imagine you and all your friends at school want to decide what games to play at break time. Instead of everyone shouting at once, you pick a few friends to be the "Deciders." These Deciders listen to what everyone wants, and then they make the big rules, like "Today we play tag," or "No running on the ice."

China’s National People’s Congress is like a giant group of "Deciders" for the whole country of China. 

Just like London is a big city in the UK, China is a very, very big country with lots and lots of people. Because there are so many people, they can't all fit in one room to talk. So, they choose around 3,000 people to go to a big, important meeting in China's capital city, Beijing. 

At this meeting, they talk about how to keep everyone safe and happy. They make the big rules for the country—like rules about keeping the rivers clean, building new trains, or making sure schools have what they need. They also pick the people who will be the "bosses" of the country to make sure the rules are followed.

So, they are basically a giant team of rule-makers chosen to help look after the millions of people living in China! [end of text]


